<h2 class="wsite-content-title" style="text-align:center;"><font color="#2a2a2a">News at Your Library</font></h2>

<div class="paragraph" style="text-align:left;">&nbsp;<strong>West Grey Progress&nbsp; April 6, 2016</strong><br /><br /><strong>NATIONAL YOUTH WEEK A CHANCE TO CELEBRATE OUR YOUNG PEOPLE</strong><br />By Kimm Culkin, West Grey Library<br /><br />As National Youth Week approaches (May 1 to 7th), it&rsquo;s a great time to consider what supports we offer our young people.&nbsp; &nbsp;One of the best ways to show we care is to encourage teens to read&hellip; and to keep reading.<br />&nbsp;<br />While many bemoan the decline of reading in today&rsquo;s youth culture, the fact is that reading demands remain high, and have been increasing over the past several decades.&nbsp; Even those who haven&rsquo;t picked up a book (voluntarily) in years are reading and posting to blogs, graphic novels, sharing fan fiction, e-books, and other online creation activities.&nbsp; But books remain the backbone of reading, whether you have to (for assignments or work), want to (for interests&rsquo; sake) or need to (because reading is a fundamental way to explore others&rsquo; experiences).&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;<br />So an environment that is literacy-rich gives teens the message that it&rsquo;s worthwhile to read &ndash; and even to read for pleasure.&nbsp; Studies show that teens who enjoy reading are more likely to succeed in school and in community actions.<br />&nbsp;<br />Online, check out Michael Rosen&rsquo;s guide to reading for pleasure.&nbsp; He&rsquo;s the former Children&rsquo;s Laureate in Britain and has made it his mission to get children and youth back to reading for pleasure.<br />&nbsp;<br />Meanwhile, here is a lucky-7 assortment of traditional and not-so-traditional tips on fostering a love of reading in your teens, whether they&rsquo;re eager or reluctant to read.&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;<br /><ul><li>Model reading yourself</li><li>Make a variety of reading materials available &ndash; don&rsquo;t just rely on online sources.&nbsp; Your public library has books and magazines, as well as e-books.</li><li>Get your teen a library card &ndash; and help them get to the library, if they need a lift</li><li>Make a book &ndash; as simple as punched pages with a cover of construction paper &ndash; or as ambitious as learning bookbinding (local art supply store The Colour Jar is owned by an expert book-binder)</li><li>Collect odd, old books &ndash; Grey County has some inspiring used book stores in Durham and Williamsford, among others</li><li>Clear time and (schedule) space for reading &ndash; my mum used to leave my brother and me in the car after a trip to the library.&nbsp; We might even finish a book while we sat in the quiet and peace of a spring afternoon.&nbsp; Of course, we cracked a window.</li><li>Encourage group-based reading activities.&nbsp; These will often be at your local libraries, but teen book clubs or sharing books via a lunch-hour book swap at school are also good bets</li><li>Help your teen connect the dots between favourite movies and the books (or comics) they came from</li></ul>&nbsp;<br /><em>F</em><em>or more information, contact your local branch. In West Grey: Durham and Elmwood Resource Centre (519-369-2107), Ayton (519-665-2342) and Neustadt (519-799-5830). </em><br /><br /><br /></div>


					
				</td>				<td class="wsite-multicol-col" style="width:48.588709677418%; padding:0 15px;">
					
						

